1
00:03:04,820 --> 00:03:05,952
<i>CLAIRE: Previously...</i>

2
00:03:05,988 --> 00:03:07,521
<i>Someone tried to poison me.</i>

3
00:03:07,556 --> 00:03:08,789
For you, Madonna.

4
00:03:08,824 --> 00:03:11,910
It will change color in
the presence of poison.

5
00:03:11,126 --> 00:03:12,959
If St. Germain is behind this,

6
00:03:12,995 --> 00:03:14,728
you need to connect him to the gang,

7
00:03:14,763 --> 00:03:15,996
<i>Les Disciples.</i>

8
00:03:16,310 --> 00:03:18,965
- There's nothing in here.
- Look again, Madonna.

9
00:03:19,100 --> 00:03:21,268
- How did you do that?
- A little sleight of hand.

10
00:03:21,303 --> 00:03:24,237
Apostle spoons. Christening
gift for the bairn.

11
00:03:24,273 --> 00:03:27,740
Monsieur Forez confided
to me that he's preparing

12
00:03:27,109 --> 00:03:28,542
for multiple executions.

13
00:03:28,577 --> 00:03:30,243
You're in danger, Master Raymond.

14
00:03:30,279 --> 00:03:31,912
<i>You can't kill Randall.</i>

15
00:03:31,947 --> 00:03:33,513
It would be as if you're
killing Frank too.

16
00:03:33,549 --> 00:03:35,415
A year, not one day more.

17
00:03:35,451 --> 00:03:38,118
Milord got into a fight
with an English officer.

18
00:03:38,153 --> 00:03:40,253
(SPEAKING SOFTLY) He promised.

19
00:03:40,289 --> 00:03:43,957
(BOTH GRUNTING)

20
00:03:43,992 --> 00:03:45,992
Jamie!

21
00:03:47,296 --> 00:03:48,495
Claire!

22
00:03:50,532 --> 00:03:53,166
<i>♪ Sing me a song ♪</i>

23
00:03:53,202 --> 00:03:56,336
<i>♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪</i>

24
00:03:56,371 --> 00:03:59,172
<i>♪ Say, could that lass ♪</i>

25
00:03:59,208 --> 00:04:02,175
<i>♪ Be I? ♪</i>

26
00:04:02,211 --> 00:04:04,100
<i>♪ Merry of soul ♪</i>

27
00:04:04,460 --> 00:04:07,800
<i>♪ She sailed on a day ♪</i>

28
00:04:07,116 --> 00:04:09,149
<i>♪ Over the sea ♪</i>

29
00:04:09,184 --> 00:04:12,319
<i>♪ To Skye ♪</i>

30
00:04:12,354 --> 00:04:14,654
<i>♪ Billow and breeze ♪</i>

31
00:04:14,690 --> 00:04:17,424
<i>♪ Islands and seas ♪</i>

32
00:04:17,459 --> 00:04:22,129
<i>♪ Mountains of rain and sun ♪</i>

33
00:04:22,698 --> 00:04:25,165
<i>♪ All that was good ♪</i>

34
00:04:25,200 --> 00:04:28,100
<i>♪ All that was fair ♪</i>

35
00:04:28,360 --> 00:04:30,170
<i>♪ All that was me ♪</i>

36
00:04:30,205 --> 00:04:33,273
<i>♪ Is gone ♪</i>

37
00:04:33,308 --> 00:04:36,276
<i>(SINGING IN FRENCH)</i>

38
00:04:36,311 --> 00:04:39,312
<i>♪</i>

39
00:04:48,690 --> 00:04:52,526
<i>♪ Over the sea ♪</i>

40
00:04:52,561 --> 00:04:57,230
<i>♪ To Skye ♪</i>

41
00:04:58,133 --> 00:04:59,332
<i>♪♪</i>

42
00:04:59,357 --> 00:05:04,120
- sync and corrections by Caio -
- www.addic7ed.com -

43
00:05:07,609 --> 00:05:10,610
<i>♪</i>

44
00:05:22,524 --> 00:05:26,126
Look, Mama. What a pretty bird.

45
00:05:26,161 --> 00:05:28,295
Let me see. (GASPS)

46
00:05:28,330 --> 00:05:30,664
That is a pretty bird, isn't it?

47
00:05:30,699 --> 00:05:32,599
What kind of bird is this?

48
00:05:32,634 --> 00:05:35,702
That is a heron.

49
00:05:35,737 --> 00:05:37,671
Have you ever seen one in real life?

50
00:05:37,706 --> 00:05:39,720
Yes, I have.

51
00:05:39,107 --> 00:05:41,374
- Where?
- In Scotland.

52
00:05:41,410 --> 00:05:43,443
When were you in Scotland, Mama?

53
00:05:43,478 --> 00:05:46,546
(SIGHS)

54
00:05:46,582 --> 00:05:48,215
A long time ago.

55
00:05:48,250 --> 00:05:51,218
(SOFT GAELIC MUSIC)

56
00:05:51,253 --> 00:05:54,254
<i>♪</i>

57
00:06:26,355 --> 00:06:29,489
Claire?

58
00:06:29,524 --> 00:06:33,526
(INDISTINCT MUTTERING)

59
00:06:35,631 --> 00:06:37,364
<i>Be still, my child.</i>

60
00:06:37,399 --> 00:06:40,367
My baby.

61
00:06:40,402 --> 00:06:42,769
I am here.

62
00:06:42,804 --> 00:06:47,741
(INDISTINCT MUTTERING)

63
00:06:47,776 --> 00:06:50,543
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

64
00:06:50,579 --> 00:06:52,779
We will take care of you.

65
00:06:52,814 --> 00:06:54,147
Jamie.

66
00:06:54,182 --> 00:06:55,548
Monsieur Forez is working.

67
00:06:55,584 --> 00:06:56,750
(WHIMPERING)

68
00:06:56,785 --> 00:06:58,184
My baby...

69
00:06:58,220 --> 00:07:01,454
You must stay quiet. You must.

70
00:07:07,529 --> 00:07:09,529
I am here.

71
00:07:19,641 --> 00:07:22,609
(SOFT MUSIC)

72
00:07:22,644 --> 00:07:25,645
<i>♪</i>

73
00:07:46,668 --> 00:07:49,669
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

74
00:08:02,250 --> 00:08:05,185
<i>♪♪</i>

75
00:08:34,683 --> 00:08:37,684
(PANICKED BREATHING)

76
00:08:40,756 --> 00:08:44,190
Where's my baby?

77
00:08:44,226 --> 00:08:47,193
Wh... where is my baby?

78
00:08:47,229 --> 00:08:48,828
<i>Chère</i> Madame,

79
00:08:48,864 --> 00:08:50,430
do not trouble yourself.

80
00:08:50,465 --> 00:08:51,798
You must save your strength.

81
00:08:51,833 --> 00:08:53,833
Where's my baby?

82
00:08:57,939 --> 00:08:59,672
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

83
00:08:59,708 --> 00:09:02,642
I don't want any water. I...

84
00:09:02,677 --> 00:09:05,478
I want my baby.

85
00:09:05,514 --> 00:09:07,414
I am sorry, Madame.

86
00:09:07,449 --> 00:09:10,216
She has joined the angels.

87
00:09:10,252 --> 00:09:13,920
She was...

88
00:09:33,875 --> 00:09:37,477
(WHISPERING) No. No.

89
00:09:39,614 --> 00:09:41,581
It's not possible.

90
00:09:55,864 --> 00:09:58,998
I want my baby.

91
00:09:59,340 --> 00:10:01,670
My... bring me my baby.

92
00:10:01,102 --> 00:10:04,938
(WHIMPERING) Bring me my baby.

93
00:10:04,973 --> 00:10:06,272
Bring me my baby!

94
00:10:06,308 --> 00:10:07,874
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

95
00:10:07,909 --> 00:10:12,450
I want my baby! Baby!

96
00:10:12,800 --> 00:10:13,847
(STATUE SHATTERING)

97
00:10:27,929 --> 00:10:30,597
Shh.

98
00:10:30,632 --> 00:10:32,999
Shh.

99
00:10:33,340 --> 00:10:34,801
(SPEAKING SOFTLY) Where is she now?

100
00:10:34,836 --> 00:10:36,703
I baptized her.

101
00:10:36,738 --> 00:10:39,405
And gave her a name.

102
00:10:39,441 --> 00:10:42,800
Faith.

103
00:10:42,430 --> 00:10:43,743
You must understand,

104
00:10:43,778 --> 00:10:46,913
it is illegal unless
the child is living.

105
00:10:46,948 --> 00:10:51,918
But I wanted her to be
buried in hallowed ground.

106
00:10:51,953 --> 00:10:53,586
This,<i> ma chère,</i>

107
00:10:53,622 --> 00:10:57,857
will stay between you, me, and God.

108
00:10:57,893 --> 00:11:00,960
(RASPY BREATHING)

109
00:11:02,931 --> 00:11:05,131
<i>Mère</i> Hildegarde...

110
00:11:09,700 --> 00:11:11,738
This is Father Laurentin.

111
00:11:11,773 --> 00:11:13,706
It is customary to perform

112
00:11:13,742 --> 00:11:16,543
an unction of the sick, my child.

113
00:11:16,578 --> 00:11:19,379
It has been several days now.

114
00:11:19,414 --> 00:11:21,514
Your fever is very high.

115
00:11:21,550 --> 00:11:24,551
It is wise to prepare the soul.

116
00:11:26,688 --> 00:11:29,455
I need my husband.

117
00:11:29,491 --> 00:11:32,792
I'm sorry,<i> ma chère,</i>
there has been no word.

118
00:11:43,638 --> 00:11:47,407
My sins are all I have left.

119
00:11:47,442 --> 00:11:50,410
(SOFT MUSIC)

120
00:11:50,445 --> 00:11:53,446
<i>♪</i>

121
00:12:02,190 --> 00:12:05,191
(SPEAKING LATIN)

122
00:12:07,762 --> 00:12:10,897
- Amen.
- Amen.

123
00:12:10,932 --> 00:12:13,933
Bouton...

124
00:12:15,937 --> 00:12:18,938
(RASPY BREATHING)

125
00:12:28,850 --> 00:12:31,851
(WHIMPERING)

126
00:12:40,161 --> 00:12:41,794
(DOG GROWLING)

127
00:12:45,900 --> 00:12:48,568
(WHIMPERING)

128
00:12:48,603 --> 00:12:50,536
(SPEAKING SOFTLY) Be still now.

129
00:12:50,572 --> 00:12:52,380
- Jamie...
- Shh, shh, shh.

130
00:12:52,730 --> 00:12:53,573
Hush, Madonna.

131
00:12:53,608 --> 00:12:56,275
If they find me here, I'm finished.

132
00:12:58,647 --> 00:13:00,580
Master Raymond.

133
00:13:00,615 --> 00:13:02,682
Tell me what you see, Madonna.

134
00:13:08,556 --> 00:13:11,524
CLAIRE: Oh, wings.

135
00:13:19,340 --> 00:13:21,567
Blue wings.

136
00:13:21,603 --> 00:13:25,571
Mm, blue with the color of healing.

137
00:13:25,607 --> 00:13:29,575
The wings will carry your
pain away, if you let them.

138
00:13:29,611 --> 00:13:33,212
<i>CLAIRE: A white hotness
burned deep in my bones.</i>

139
00:13:33,248 --> 00:13:35,148
<i>I knew what it was.</i>

140
00:13:35,183 --> 00:13:37,283
<i>Puerperal fever.</i>

141
00:13:37,318 --> 00:13:39,185
<i>The baby had come,</i>

142
00:13:39,220 --> 00:13:41,988
<i>but part of the placenta had not.</i>

143
00:13:42,230 --> 00:13:44,857
<i>It festered inside my womb,</i>

144
00:13:44,893 --> 00:13:49,262
<i>but as Raymond's hands moved
over the meridians of my body,</i>

145
00:13:49,297 --> 00:13:52,980
<i>I could feel the tiny
deaths of the bacteria</i>

146
00:13:52,133 --> 00:13:55,234
<i>that inhabited my
blood, small explosions</i>

147
00:13:55,270 --> 00:13:58,671
<i>as each scintilla of
infection disappeared.</i>

148
00:13:58,707 --> 00:14:01,740
<i>The fever drained from my bones,</i>

149
00:14:01,109 --> 00:14:03,342
<i>and my tortured body relaxed gratefully</i>

150
00:14:03,378 --> 00:14:05,745
<i>into the frame of his hands,</i>

151
00:14:05,780 --> 00:14:09,282
<i>melting and reforming like molded wax.</i>

152
00:14:13,154 --> 00:14:15,888
(GROANS)

153
00:14:15,924 --> 00:14:18,958
(INHALES DEEPLY)

154
00:14:18,993 --> 00:14:21,828
Call him.

155
00:14:21,863 --> 00:14:25,898
(GROANS)

156
00:14:25,934 --> 00:14:29,202
- Call to him.
- (GRUNTING)

157
00:14:29,237 --> 00:14:32,905
Jamie!

158
00:14:32,941 --> 00:14:36,175
(GRUNTING)

159
00:14:36,211 --> 00:14:37,777
<i>CLAIRE: I don't know what he did</i>

160
00:14:37,812 --> 00:14:39,212
<i>or how he did it...</i>

161
00:14:39,247 --> 00:14:40,980
(DOOR OPENS)

162
00:14:41,150 --> 00:14:42,215
<i>But he healed me.</i>

163
00:14:42,250 --> 00:14:43,883
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

164
00:14:43,918 --> 00:14:48,221
<i>Once more, he saved my life.</i>

165
00:14:48,256 --> 00:14:49,989
Madame?

166
00:15:09,944 --> 00:15:13,112
I must go now. Be well, Madonna.

167
00:15:13,148 --> 00:15:15,648
I am no Madonna.

168
00:15:15,683 --> 00:15:17,383
I have no child.

169
00:15:17,418 --> 00:15:18,818
I didn't call you Madonna

170
00:15:18,853 --> 00:15:21,988
because you were with child, my dear.

171
00:15:22,230 --> 00:15:24,390
Everyone has a color about them,

172
00:15:24,425 --> 00:15:27,794
all around them like a cloud.

173
00:15:27,829 --> 00:15:29,162
Yours is blue.

174
00:15:29,197 --> 00:15:31,300
Like the Virgin's cloak.

175
00:15:31,650 --> 00:15:34,330
Like my own.

176
00:15:34,680 --> 00:15:36,269
You shouldn't have come.

177
00:15:36,304 --> 00:15:38,370
It's too dangerous.

178
00:15:38,720 --> 00:15:39,405
You were right about the king.

179
00:15:39,440 --> 00:15:41,274
He wants blood now.

180
00:15:43,452 --> 00:15:48,880
But these are things you
do for your friends.

181
00:15:48,116 --> 00:15:50,950
Will I ever see you again?

182
00:15:50,985 --> 00:15:54,987
As I told you before, we
will see each other again.

183
00:15:58,259 --> 00:16:02,795
(DOOR OPENING, FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

184
00:16:13,875 --> 00:16:15,174
(GASPS)

185
00:16:30,910 --> 00:16:34,727
Mère, has there been any
word from Monsieur Fraser?

186
00:16:34,762 --> 00:16:37,196
He is unable to come, Madame.

187
00:16:37,232 --> 00:16:41,670
He was arrested for dueling
with the English captain,

188
00:16:41,102 --> 00:16:45,938
and is being detained in the
Bastille Saint-Antoine.

189
00:16:45,974 --> 00:16:47,874
For how long?

190
00:16:47,909 --> 00:16:50,476
Dueling is a serious offense.

191
00:16:50,511 --> 00:16:53,813
I'm afraid your husband
will remain in prison

192
00:16:53,848 --> 00:16:56,349
at the king's pleasure.

193
00:16:56,384 --> 00:16:59,385
If your husband had killed his opponent,

194
00:16:59,420 --> 00:17:02,822
the penalty would have been much worse.

195
00:17:02,857 --> 00:17:04,824
He's not dead?

196
00:17:04,859 --> 00:17:07,526
The English captain?

197
00:17:07,562 --> 00:17:09,395
He is badly wounded,

198
00:17:09,430 --> 00:17:12,431
and the British ambassador
begged for him to be allowed

199
00:17:12,467 --> 00:17:16,402
to recover from his injuries in England.

200
00:17:16,437 --> 00:17:19,338
<i>CLAIRE: So Jack Randall was still alive.</i>

201
00:17:19,374 --> 00:17:22,308
<i>The cat with nine lives.</i>

202
00:17:22,343 --> 00:17:26,379
<i>And thus, so was Frank.</i>

203
00:17:26,414 --> 00:17:27,980
<i>But at what cost?</i>

204
00:17:28,160 --> 00:17:31,350
That is fortunate, no?

205
00:17:31,386 --> 00:17:32,551
Yes.

206
00:17:35,290 --> 00:17:38,900
Fortunate.

207
00:17:38,126 --> 00:17:40,993
But my husband betrayed me, Mother.

208
00:17:41,290 --> 00:17:44,830
Revenge mattered more to him than me...

209
00:17:46,301 --> 00:17:48,868
or his child.

210
00:17:48,903 --> 00:17:52,405
How so?

211
00:17:52,440 --> 00:17:56,208
One year of grace

212
00:17:56,244 --> 00:18:00,460
is all I asked,

213
00:18:00,810 --> 00:18:04,183
to which he agreed.

214
00:18:04,218 --> 00:18:06,385
One year.

215
00:18:06,421 --> 00:18:11,157
He may as well have run
his sword through me.

216
00:18:14,562 --> 00:18:18,297
God says we must revel in mercy.

217
00:18:18,333 --> 00:18:21,500
Tread sins underfoot

218
00:18:21,536 --> 00:18:26,405
and hurl iniquities into the sea.

219
00:18:26,441 --> 00:18:30,843
I'm not sure there's a sea deep enough.

220
00:18:30,878 --> 00:18:33,813
(SOFT MUSIC)

221
00:18:33,848 --> 00:18:36,849
<i>♪</i>

222
00:18:44,959 --> 00:18:47,560
<i>CLAIRE: I laid in that bed for weeks.</i>

223
00:18:47,595 --> 00:18:52,298
<i>My body had healed. My soul had not.</i>

224
00:18:52,333 --> 00:18:55,267
<i>One day Fergus came.</i>

225
00:18:55,303 --> 00:19:00,239
<i>He brought flowers and
asked me to come home.</i>

226
00:19:00,274 --> 00:19:04,643
<i>I'd lost my husband and my child.</i>

227
00:19:04,679 --> 00:19:07,546
<i>Where else could I go?</i>

228
00:19:07,582 --> 00:19:10,583
<i>♪</i>

229
00:19:10,618 --> 00:19:13,586
(SOMBER MUSIC)

230
00:19:13,621 --> 00:19:16,622
<i>♪</i>

231
00:20:22,323 --> 00:20:25,324
(SOBBING)

232
00:20:32,767 --> 00:20:35,468
Welcome home...

233
00:20:35,503 --> 00:20:37,369
Milady.

234
00:20:37,405 --> 00:20:40,406
<i>♪</i>

235
00:20:54,722 --> 00:20:57,656
Thank you, Magnus.

236
00:20:57,692 --> 00:21:00,726
(SOMBER MUSIC)

237
00:21:00,761 --> 00:21:03,762
<i>♪</i>

238
00:21:43,738 --> 00:21:45,471
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

239
00:21:50,444 --> 00:21:52,578
Thank you, Fergus.

240
00:21:52,613 --> 00:21:54,246
That was nice.

241
00:22:05,793 --> 00:22:08,694
(OMINOUS MUSIC)

242
00:22:08,729 --> 00:22:11,730
<i>♪</i>

243
00:22:16,837 --> 00:22:18,470
What is it?

244
00:22:18,506 --> 00:22:21,473
N... nothing, Milady.

245
00:22:24,245 --> 00:22:25,911
(DOOR CLOSING)

246
00:22:59,947 --> 00:23:02,881
(SOMBER MUSIC)

247
00:23:02,917 --> 00:23:05,918
<i>♪</i>

248
00:23:10,858 --> 00:23:13,325
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

249
00:23:13,361 --> 00:23:14,560
(GRUNTS)

250
00:23:20,835 --> 00:23:23,836
(FAINT WHIMPERING)

251
00:23:43,257 --> 00:23:45,691
<i>FERGUS: No!</i>

252
00:23:45,726 --> 00:23:49,495
<i>What is he doing?</i>

253
00:23:49,530 --> 00:23:51,297
Stop!

254
00:23:51,332 --> 00:23:54,733
(WHIMPERING)

255
00:23:54,769 --> 00:23:57,903
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

256
00:23:57,938 --> 00:24:01,473
Fergus?

257
00:24:01,509 --> 00:24:02,741
Wake up.

258
00:24:02,777 --> 00:24:05,778
It's just a bad dream.

259
00:24:08,482 --> 00:24:11,517
Do you want to tell me about it?

260
00:24:11,552 --> 00:24:15,587
No. No, Milady.

261
00:24:15,623 --> 00:24:19,425
Might make you feel better.

262
00:24:19,460 --> 00:24:23,329
It's... it... it's not just a dream.

263
00:24:25,800 --> 00:24:28,467
What is it?

264
00:24:28,502 --> 00:24:30,936
The... the Englishman, Milady.

265
00:24:35,609 --> 00:24:37,609
What Englishman?

266
00:24:39,714 --> 00:24:41,680
Fergus, tell me.

267
00:24:45,319 --> 00:24:49,355
I-I went with Milord to...
to Maison Elise.

268
00:24:49,390 --> 00:24:51,323
<i>Prince Charles owed money.</i>

269
00:24:51,359 --> 00:24:52,391
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

270
00:24:52,426 --> 00:24:53,992
<i>FERGUS: He told me to wait.</i>

271
00:24:54,280 --> 00:24:55,961
<i>Milord told me to stay put,</i>

272
00:24:55,996 --> 00:24:58,564
<i>but I have a talent for stealing</i>

273
00:24:58,599 --> 00:25:00,532
<i>and I couldn't resist.</i>

274
00:25:00,568 --> 00:25:04,837
O... one of the rooms was open...

275
00:25:04,872 --> 00:25:08,307
<i>and I saw a bottle of perfume there.</i>

276
00:25:08,342 --> 00:25:11,744
<i>I-I-I wanted to bring
it to Milady as a gift.</i>

277
00:25:11,779 --> 00:25:13,579
<i>It smelled so nice.</i>

278
00:25:13,614 --> 00:25:15,414
<i>I put it in my pocket.</i>

279
00:25:15,449 --> 00:25:19,451
I kept the bottle, but...

280
00:25:19,487 --> 00:25:21,120
but I was too afraid to give it to you

281
00:25:21,155 --> 00:25:22,554
after what happened.

282
00:25:32,166 --> 00:25:34,466
It's lavender, Milady.

283
00:25:37,405 --> 00:25:39,805
When I turned around,

284
00:25:39,840 --> 00:25:42,875
<i>he was there. The Englishman.</i>

285
00:25:42,910 --> 00:25:47,546
You're not what I ordered.

286
00:25:47,581 --> 00:25:50,949
But, um...

287
00:25:50,985 --> 00:25:52,551
no, you'll do.

288
00:25:52,586 --> 00:25:54,987
(WHISPERING) Jesus Christ.

289
00:25:55,220 --> 00:25:57,623
I-I tried to get away, I swear I did.

290
00:25:57,658 --> 00:25:59,458
I told him Milord was there,

291
00:25:59,493 --> 00:26:02,995
but he... he wouldn't listen.

292
00:26:03,300 --> 00:26:06,632
He said that h-h-h-he wanted me to...

293
00:26:11,972 --> 00:26:16,875
I can't say it in front of a lady.

294
00:26:16,911 --> 00:26:20,646
(GRUNTS) Stop! Stop!

295
00:26:20,681 --> 00:26:23,810
Why... why didn't you
tell me this sooner?

296
00:26:23,117 --> 00:26:26,118
I-I wanted to, but...

297
00:26:28,155 --> 00:26:29,922
but I was ashamed.

298
00:26:29,957 --> 00:26:31,590
It's all right, Fergus.

299
00:26:31,625 --> 00:26:35,160
No! No, it's not.

300
00:26:35,196 --> 00:26:37,563
It's all my fault.

301
00:26:37,598 --> 00:26:40,799
I should have kept quiet.

302
00:26:40,835 --> 00:26:42,801
I didn't cry or scream at first,

303
00:26:42,837 --> 00:26:47,473
but... I couldn't help it.

304
00:26:47,508 --> 00:26:50,209
Stop! Stop! Stop!

305
00:26:50,244 --> 00:26:52,878
<i>Milord!</i>

306
00:26:52,913 --> 00:26:56,181
Milord heard it and...

307
00:26:56,217 --> 00:26:57,783
and he came running.

308
00:26:57,818 --> 00:26:59,885
Milord!

309
00:27:02,256 --> 00:27:05,257
(BOTH GRUNTING)

310
00:27:07,962 --> 00:27:09,628
<i>I hid under the dressing table.</i>

311
00:27:09,663 --> 00:27:13,131
- (GRUNTING)
- Get off!

312
00:27:13,167 --> 00:27:15,934
<i>Then the fight was broken up.</i>

313
00:27:15,970 --> 00:27:19,538
A-as soon as Milord was taken away,

314
00:27:19,573 --> 00:27:22,808
I heard him challenge the
Englishman to a duel.

315
00:27:22,843 --> 00:27:25,644
You sick bastard!

316
00:27:25,679 --> 00:27:28,814
A duel! I demand a duel!

317
00:27:28,849 --> 00:27:30,949
No! (GRUNTS)

318
00:27:30,985 --> 00:27:33,285
<i>And then he was taken away.</i>

319
00:27:36,857 --> 00:27:38,857
(GROANS)

320
00:27:38,893 --> 00:27:41,260
It's not your fault, Fergus.

321
00:27:41,295 --> 00:27:42,995
I-I didn't know.

322
00:27:43,300 --> 00:27:46,532
I didn't know he would go
to fight the Englishman.

323
00:27:46,567 --> 00:27:48,534
I didn't know.

324
00:27:48,569 --> 00:27:50,969
A... and now Milord is gone.

325
00:27:51,500 --> 00:27:55,173
He will never come back.

326
00:27:55,209 --> 00:27:56,642
Come here.

327
00:27:56,677 --> 00:27:58,277
Oh, it's all right.

328
00:28:04,885 --> 00:28:09,154
A private audience with the king?

329
00:28:09,189 --> 00:28:11,223
You have mentioned you
are the goddaughter

330
00:28:11,258 --> 00:28:12,891
of the Old Sun King.

331
00:28:12,927 --> 00:28:16,995
Surely you have an entrée
or know someone who does.

332
00:28:19,700 --> 00:28:24,202
It is possible.

333
00:28:24,238 --> 00:28:26,672
I wish to petition for
my husband's release

334
00:28:26,707 --> 00:28:28,840
from the Bastille.

335
00:28:28,876 --> 00:28:33,211
So, ma chère, you have
found a deep enough sea.

336
00:28:36,150 --> 00:28:39,952
I learned the reason
he broke his promise.

337
00:28:39,987 --> 00:28:42,521
I was angry at him.

338
00:28:42,556 --> 00:28:44,957
Still am.

339
00:28:44,992 --> 00:28:47,960
But he is the father of my child.

340
00:28:51,298 --> 00:28:56,268
His Majesty is a mercurial man.

341
00:28:56,303 --> 00:29:00,772
There is a price to such requests.

342
00:29:00,808 --> 00:29:02,774
Which is?

343
00:29:02,810 --> 00:29:06,440
The king may expect to lie with you.

344
00:29:12,953 --> 00:29:17,923
If it comes to sacrificing
my virtue, Mother,

345
00:29:17,958 --> 00:29:19,958
I'll add it to the list of things

346
00:29:19,994 --> 00:29:22,600
I have already lost in Paris.

347
00:29:39,713 --> 00:29:42,648
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

348
00:29:42,683 --> 00:29:45,684
<i>♪</i>

349
00:30:10,778 --> 00:30:13,645
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

350
00:30:13,681 --> 00:30:16,815
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

351
00:30:16,850 --> 00:30:20,786
Madame Claire Fraser,
Lady Broch Tuarach.

352
00:30:40,407 --> 00:30:41,940
No.

353
00:31:37,831 --> 00:31:39,431
(SNIFFING)

354
00:31:42,202 --> 00:31:43,368
Mmm.

355
00:31:52,640 --> 00:31:56,410
Now, tell me what it is
that I may do for you.

356
00:31:58,680 --> 00:32:02,816
My husband is in the Bastille.

357
00:32:02,841 --> 00:32:04,908
For dueling.

358
00:32:04,933 --> 00:32:09,669
Your husband has broken a royal decree.

359
00:32:09,897 --> 00:32:12,531
I understand that.

360
00:32:12,566 --> 00:32:16,968
But he was provoked.

361
00:32:17,400 --> 00:32:19,838
As you know, he is a Scot.

362
00:32:19,873 --> 00:32:21,907
They are most fierce where questions

363
00:32:21,942 --> 00:32:24,109
of their honor are concerned.

364
00:32:24,144 --> 00:32:26,411
Quite so.

365
00:32:26,446 --> 00:32:30,182
Quite so, Madame.

366
00:32:30,217 --> 00:32:34,920
- However...
- I would be most grateful...

367
00:32:34,955 --> 00:32:36,588
Your Majesty.

368
00:32:45,632 --> 00:32:48,466
Is this his ring?

369
00:32:48,502 --> 00:32:50,502
Yes, Sire.

370
00:32:54,107 --> 00:32:57,108
And this other one?

371
00:32:59,913 --> 00:33:03,480
I was married once before.

372
00:33:05,180 --> 00:33:08,453
And yet you still wear his ring.

373
00:33:08,488 --> 00:33:11,489
Your loyalty is most...

374
00:33:11,525 --> 00:33:13,525
noteworthy.

375
00:33:36,550 --> 00:33:40,385
I am inclined towards mercy,

376
00:33:40,420 --> 00:33:42,320
<i>ma chère Madame,</i>

377
00:33:42,356 --> 00:33:45,557
but...

378
00:33:45,592 --> 00:33:48,627
<i>CLAIRE: He was called
Louis the Well-Beloved.</i>

379
00:33:48,662 --> 00:33:51,229
<i>His rule was absolute.</i>

380
00:33:51,265 --> 00:33:53,231
<i>He could free Jamie with a word</i>

381
00:33:53,267 --> 00:33:55,166
<i>or kill him.</i>

382
00:33:55,202 --> 00:33:57,469
<i>He could do with me as he liked.</i>

383
00:33:57,504 --> 00:34:00,772
<i>I waited to see what His
Majesty's pleasure might be.</i>

384
00:34:00,807 --> 00:34:04,309
Tell me, if I was to grant your request

385
00:34:04,344 --> 00:34:07,679
to free your husband...

386
00:34:07,714 --> 00:34:11,983
would you be inclined to grant
me a small favor in return?

387
00:34:14,521 --> 00:34:19,524
I am at Your Majesty's
complete disposal.

388
00:34:20,560 --> 00:34:25,230
Ah. <i>Très bien.</i>

389
00:34:25,265 --> 00:34:29,334
<i>Très bien, ma chère.</i>

390
00:34:29,369 --> 00:34:31,469
Come.

391
00:34:56,296 --> 00:34:59,431
So pale.

392
00:34:59,466 --> 00:35:03,234
So fine.

393
00:35:03,270 --> 00:35:07,672
I can see why they call
you <i>La Dame Blanche.</i>

394
00:35:07,708 --> 00:35:10,709
(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC)

395
00:35:10,744 --> 00:35:13,712
<i>♪</i>

396
00:36:03,397 --> 00:36:07,399
The king asks that you give us
the benefit of your skills.

397
00:36:07,434 --> 00:36:09,167
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

398
00:36:12,270 --> 00:36:14,300
<i>CLAIRE: When I saw Monsieur Forez,</i>

399
00:36:14,280 --> 00:36:15,928
<i>the king's executioner,</i>

400
00:36:16,118 --> 00:36:19,353
<i>I knew his presence could
mean only one thing:</i>

401
00:36:19,388 --> 00:36:22,256
<i>there would be death here today.</i>

402
00:36:22,291 --> 00:36:25,426
I'm not sure what you mean, Sire.

403
00:36:47,216 --> 00:36:51,518
Maître Raymond et Comte St. Germain,

404
00:37:17,130 --> 00:37:21,548
We have no quarrel with the
proper search for wisdom.

405
00:37:21,584 --> 00:37:24,618
But while much good may be found,

406
00:37:24,654 --> 00:37:27,554
so, too, may evil be discovered.

407
00:37:27,590 --> 00:37:31,659
And the search for
wisdom be perverted into

408
00:37:31,694 --> 00:37:33,928
the desire for power and wealth

409
00:37:33,963 --> 00:37:37,197
for one's own depraved
and immoral purpose.

410
00:38:06,128 --> 00:38:08,329
(WHISPERING) Jesus H. Roosevelt Christ.

411
00:38:08,364 --> 00:38:10,497
I beseech you to use your talents,

412
00:38:10,533 --> 00:38:12,700
look into their souls

413
00:38:12,735 --> 00:38:15,569
and if there is darkness within,

414
00:38:15,604 --> 00:38:18,172
they will be handed
over to M'sieur Forez

415
00:38:18,207 --> 00:38:19,707
and put to death.

416
00:38:19,742 --> 00:38:22,710
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

417
00:38:22,745 --> 00:38:25,746
<i>♪</i>

418
00:38:28,117 --> 00:38:30,684
It will be an honor

419
00:38:30,720 --> 00:38:33,654
to assist Your Majesty in this task.

420
00:38:33,689 --> 00:38:36,230
Very well.

421
00:38:36,580 --> 00:38:37,624
Let us commence.

422
00:39:10,326 --> 00:39:13,260
I see a shadow...

423
00:39:13,295 --> 00:39:17,431
behind your eyes, Comte.

424
00:39:17,466 --> 00:39:19,433
(NERVOUS CHUCKLE)

425
00:39:26,409 --> 00:39:28,442
(NERVOUS CHUCKLE)

426
00:39:33,449 --> 00:39:36,683
I see an image.

427
00:39:36,719 --> 00:39:40,320
A gang of men in the street...

428
00:39:40,356 --> 00:39:42,156
dressed as aristocrats,

429
00:39:42,191 --> 00:39:44,625
but wearing masks.

430
00:39:46,695 --> 00:39:49,396
There is a name in
your mind, Monsieur...

431
00:39:53,536 --> 00:39:55,803
- "Les Disciples."
- (SCOFFS)

432
00:40:00,709 --> 00:40:03,343
What do you know of "Les
Disciples," Monsieur?

433
00:40:03,379 --> 00:40:06,814
I know nothing of these
"Disciples" of which you speak.

434
00:40:06,849 --> 00:40:09,917
- You are lying, sir.
- I am not lying.

435
00:40:09,952 --> 00:40:14,721
I am not lying! I am not lying, Sire!

436
00:40:14,757 --> 00:40:18,225
This woman is a liar and a witch.

437
00:40:18,260 --> 00:40:21,395
This woman has also been known
to drink poison and survive.

438
00:40:21,430 --> 00:40:23,230
And how do you come to this knowledge?

439
00:40:23,265 --> 00:40:26,667
Because I gave her the poison myself.

440
00:40:33,375 --> 00:40:36,510
She tried to ruin my livelihood.

441
00:40:36,545 --> 00:40:40,214
She had my ship destroyed
with her false condemnations.

442
00:40:40,249 --> 00:40:43,484
She is a witch.

443
00:40:43,519 --> 00:40:45,552
And she doesn't deny it.

444
00:40:48,591 --> 00:40:50,224
(SCOFFS)

445
00:40:50,259 --> 00:40:52,960
No.

446
00:40:52,995 --> 00:40:57,498
I don't deny it.

447
00:40:57,533 --> 00:41:02,469
<i>La Dame Blanche</i> is a white witch,

448
00:41:02,505 --> 00:41:04,838
and I practice...

449
00:41:04,874 --> 00:41:08,709
white magic, Sire.

450
00:41:10,980 --> 00:41:14,581
Madame Fraser

451
00:41:14,617 --> 00:41:17,417
is not on trial here.

452
00:41:19,955 --> 00:41:23,557
<i>CLAIRE: Even knowing St.
Germain tried to poison me,</i>

453
00:41:23,592 --> 00:41:28,362
<i>I found it hard to condemn
him cold-bloodedly to death.</i>

454
00:41:28,397 --> 00:41:30,631
(SPEAKING SOFTLY) I see
darkness in his soul.

455
00:41:38,914 --> 00:41:42,415
Also in his.

456
00:41:42,912 --> 00:41:44,912
But only the normal darkness

457
00:41:44,947 --> 00:41:48,582
that lives in the souls of...

458
00:41:48,617 --> 00:41:50,617
all men.

459
00:41:58,360 --> 00:41:59,993
Even a king's.

460
00:42:07,503 --> 00:42:11,371
For without darkness...

461
00:42:11,407 --> 00:42:13,473
there can be no light.

462
00:42:16,412 --> 00:42:19,713
Nevertheless, if I am
to cleanse this city,

463
00:42:19,748 --> 00:42:21,810
I must make an example.

464
00:42:21,116 --> 00:42:22,282
(SCOFFS)

465
00:42:24,887 --> 00:42:29,356
Perhaps we can aid your decision.

466
00:42:31,327 --> 00:42:34,328
(RUMBLING)

467
00:42:39,335 --> 00:42:42,302
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

468
00:42:42,338 --> 00:42:45,339
<i>♪</i>

469
00:42:48,510 --> 00:42:51,345
The Bible claims that a true believer

470
00:42:51,380 --> 00:42:55,415
can handle serpents and
they will not harm him,

471
00:42:55,451 --> 00:42:58,619
for they are the servants of God.

472
00:43:05,828 --> 00:43:09,960
Perhaps, Your Majesty,

473
00:43:09,131 --> 00:43:11,980
I may suggest another test.

474
00:43:18,641 --> 00:43:21,475
It is true I drank the Comte's poison

475
00:43:21,510 --> 00:43:23,510
and it did not kill me.

476
00:43:23,545 --> 00:43:27,481
Let him drink mine and see what happens.

477
00:43:27,516 --> 00:43:29,950
Let them both drink it.

478
00:43:29,985 --> 00:43:31,451
With your permission?

479
00:43:38,661 --> 00:43:39,860
Very well.

480
00:43:41,764 --> 00:43:43,497
<i>CLAIRE: I decided to take a page</i>

481
00:43:43,532 --> 00:43:46,330
<i>out of Master Raymond's
book, so to speak.</i>

482
00:43:46,680 --> 00:43:49,503
<i>I looked through the evidence,
the remnants from his shop</i>

483
00:43:49,538 --> 00:43:51,838
<i>and found the herb I was looking for.</i>

484
00:43:51,874 --> 00:43:54,675
<i>Bitter cascara.</i>

485
00:43:54,710 --> 00:43:57,440
<i>I knew the cascara would
make both men ill,</i>

486
00:43:57,790 --> 00:43:59,120
<i>but wouldn't kill them.</i>

487
00:43:59,480 --> 00:44:01,481
<i>And perhaps Louis, having had his show,</i>

488
00:44:01,517 --> 00:44:04,718
<i>would be appeased and set them free.</i>

489
00:44:08,900 --> 00:44:11,725
This potion will give
you your answers, Sire.

490
00:44:15,597 --> 00:44:18,932
We may have a death...

491
00:44:18,967 --> 00:44:20,967
or two.

492
00:44:23,172 --> 00:44:25,605
But I ask one thing:

493
00:44:25,641 --> 00:44:27,974
if both these men survive,

494
00:44:28,100 --> 00:44:30,770
you will set them free.

495
00:44:33,649 --> 00:44:37,751
We shall see if it pleases the king.

496
00:44:41,790 --> 00:44:44,758
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

497
00:44:44,793 --> 00:44:47,794
<i>♪</i>

498
00:45:15,524 --> 00:45:19,793
(CHOKES)

499
00:45:19,828 --> 00:45:22,662
(GAGS)

500
00:45:22,698 --> 00:45:24,640
(COUGHS)

501
00:45:24,990 --> 00:45:27,100
(GRUNTING)

502
00:45:33,275 --> 00:45:36,276
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

503
00:45:42,351 --> 00:45:45,318
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

504
00:45:45,354 --> 00:45:48,321
<i>♪</i>

505
00:46:03,305 --> 00:46:07,741
<i>CLAIRE: I never saw Raymond add
anything to it, no one had.</i>

506
00:46:07,776 --> 00:46:10,877
<i>It was another amazing
feat, a sleight of hand</i>

507
00:46:10,913 --> 00:46:13,130
<i>like the one he'd shown me in his shop.</i>

508
00:46:23,325 --> 00:46:27,930
Give him the cup.

509
00:46:27,129 --> 00:46:28,328
Hand it to him.

510
00:46:34,403 --> 00:46:36,903
<i>CLAIRE: All I knew was that this time,</i>

511
00:46:36,939 --> 00:46:41,708
<i>inside the cup, was death.</i>

512
00:46:41,743 --> 00:46:43,710
<i>St. Germain knew it too.</i>

513
00:46:43,745 --> 00:46:45,745
(NERVOUS CHUCKLE)

514
00:46:49,718 --> 00:46:52,385
Oh, well...

515
00:47:29,324 --> 00:47:32,292
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

516
00:47:32,327 --> 00:47:35,328
<i>♪</i>

517
00:47:45,274 --> 00:47:47,908
(CUP CLATTERING)

518
00:47:47,943 --> 00:47:50,944
<i>♪</i>

519
00:48:00,455 --> 00:48:03,456
(GRUNTING)

520
00:48:16,710 --> 00:48:19,720
(GROANING)

521
00:48:25,800 --> 00:48:26,790
(SIGHING)

522
00:48:53,976 --> 00:48:55,275
<i>CLAIRE: Perhaps it was the shock</i>

523
00:48:55,310 --> 00:48:56,977
<i>of what I'd been through,</i>

524
00:48:57,120 --> 00:48:59,479
<i>but as Master Raymond was led away,</i>

525
00:48:59,514 --> 00:49:02,582
<i>what ran through my brain
was a line from a film.</i>

526
00:49:02,618 --> 00:49:04,384
<i>You know the one:</i>

527
00:49:04,419 --> 00:49:07,887
<i>"I'm going to miss you most of all."</i>

528
00:49:07,923 --> 00:49:09,456
(DOOR CLOSING)

529
00:49:22,537 --> 00:49:27,140
Your Majesty will honor my request?

530
00:49:27,175 --> 00:49:30,877
First, there's still a
matter of the payment.

531
00:49:52,267 --> 00:49:54,670
(GASPING)

532
00:50:03,512 --> 00:50:05,101
<i>CLAIRE: I closed my eyes</i>

533
00:50:05,126 --> 00:50:07,304
(CLASSICAL MUSIC)

534
00:50:07,329 --> 00:50:09,484
<i>and thought of England.</i>

535
00:50:10,352 --> 00:50:13,353
<i>♪</i>

536
00:50:30,105 --> 00:50:31,304
<i>♪♪</i>

537
00:50:53,950 --> 00:50:55,195
I will issue a pardon for your husband

538
00:50:55,230 --> 00:50:57,130
and arrange one with the English crown

539
00:50:57,165 --> 00:51:00,100
should you wish to return to Scotland.

540
00:51:16,151 --> 00:51:19,119
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

541
00:51:19,154 --> 00:51:22,122
<i>♪</i>

542
00:51:44,646 --> 00:51:46,179
(CLEARS THROAT)

543
00:52:54,449 --> 00:52:57,817
(CLOCK TICKING)

544
00:52:57,853 --> 00:53:02,355
I don't even know if it was a boy...

545
00:53:02,390 --> 00:53:04,390
or a girl.

546
00:53:09,531 --> 00:53:11,531
(WHISPERING) Claire?

547
00:53:14,536 --> 00:53:16,536
Will ye make me beg?

548
00:53:48,536 --> 00:53:51,905
It was a girl.

549
00:53:51,940 --> 00:53:55,808
Mother Hildegarde baptized her.

550
00:53:55,844 --> 00:53:59,512
Gave her a name.

551
00:53:59,547 --> 00:54:01,547
Faith.

552
00:54:03,551 --> 00:54:07,520
Mother Hildegarde has a
very odd sense of humor.

553
00:54:10,625 --> 00:54:12,792
She's buried in the cemetery,

554
00:54:12,827 --> 00:54:15,728
next to the convent.

555
00:54:17,933 --> 00:54:20,433
I did try to keep my promise.

556
00:54:25,307 --> 00:54:27,507
Fergus told me what happened.

557
00:54:27,542 --> 00:54:30,877
Then ye see how I couldna
let Randall go unpunished

558
00:54:30,912 --> 00:54:33,246
for what he did to the wee lad?

559
00:54:43,525 --> 00:54:45,758
Do ye hate me for it, Claire?

560
00:54:54,269 --> 00:54:56,269
(SPEAKING SOFTLY) I did hate you.

561
00:54:56,304 --> 00:54:59,305
(CLOCK TICKING)

562
00:55:02,477 --> 00:55:05,878
(INAUDIBLE)

563
00:55:05,914 --> 00:55:10,483
(CLOCK CONTINUES TICKING)

564
00:55:10,518 --> 00:55:14,721
Mother Hildegarde let me see her,

565
00:55:14,756 --> 00:55:18,324
<i>so I wouldn't have to imagine.</i>

566
00:55:18,360 --> 00:55:21,995
(EXHALES SHARPLY)

567
00:55:22,300 --> 00:55:24,300
(WHIMPERS)

568
00:55:33,641 --> 00:55:37,643
<i>CLAIRE: She was beautiful.</i>

569
00:55:37,679 --> 00:55:39,846
<i>So small.</i>

570
00:55:39,881 --> 00:55:44,884
I could cup her head in
the palm of my hand.

571
00:55:46,955 --> 00:55:51,457
The ears stuck out just a little.

572
00:55:51,493 --> 00:55:53,760
You could see the light through them.

573
00:55:53,795 --> 00:55:57,530
And the light through her skin as well.

574
00:55:57,565 --> 00:56:01,567
Like the light on a pearl

575
00:56:01,603 --> 00:56:05,838
that's still wet from the sea.

576
00:56:05,874 --> 00:56:08,808
Her eyes were closed.

577
00:56:11,613 --> 00:56:13,579
No lashes yet.

578
00:56:13,615 --> 00:56:16,349
They were slanted a bit,

579
00:56:16,384 --> 00:56:20,353
like yours.

580
00:56:20,388 --> 00:56:23,389
She had wisps of the most...

581
00:56:23,425 --> 00:56:25,958
beautiful copper hair.

582
00:56:25,994 --> 00:56:30,363
♪ Oh, I do like to be ♪

583
00:56:30,398 --> 00:56:33,800
<i>♪ Beside the seaside ♪</i>

584
00:56:33,835 --> 00:56:37,700
♪ Oh, I do like to be ♪

585
00:56:37,105 --> 00:56:40,600
♪ Beside the sea ♪

586
00:56:40,410 --> 00:56:43,476
♪ I like to walk along ♪

587
00:56:43,511 --> 00:56:46,479
♪ Prom, Prom, Prom ♪

588
00:56:46,514 --> 00:56:51,184
<i>♪ So just let me be beside the sea ♪</i>

589
00:56:58,626 --> 00:57:00,860
How long has it been?

590
00:57:01,750 --> 00:57:02,650
Since this morning.

591
00:57:40,340 --> 00:57:42,201
<i>Ma chère</i> Claire.

592
00:57:54,480 --> 00:57:58,500
She's beautiful, isn't she?

593
00:57:58,860 --> 00:58:00,153
<i>Oui.</i>

594
00:58:04,250 --> 00:58:06,759
Ten fingers.

595
00:58:06,794 --> 00:58:08,728
And ten toes.

596
00:58:12,700 --> 00:58:14,700
She's an angel.

597
00:58:23,440 --> 00:58:25,440
May I hold her?

598
00:58:35,557 --> 00:58:38,524
(SOMBER MUSIC)

599
00:58:38,560 --> 00:58:41,561
<i>♪ ♪</i>

600
00:58:54,542 --> 00:58:57,543
(SOBBING)

601
00:59:30,178 --> 00:59:33,179
(SOBBING)

602
00:59:58,206 --> 01:00:01,274
So yes...

603
01:00:05,460 --> 01:00:08,414
I hated you.

604
01:00:11,152 --> 01:00:13,152
Aye.

605
01:00:24,832 --> 01:00:26,832
But...

606
01:00:31,639 --> 01:00:33,806
it was me...

607
01:00:35,430 --> 01:00:37,337
who asked the impossible of you.

608
01:00:38,398 --> 01:00:42,566
It was me that put Frank
before our family.

609
01:00:42,821 --> 01:00:46,289
It was me...

610
01:00:46,645 --> 01:00:48,612
who followed you to the woods.

611
01:00:48,637 --> 01:00:50,970
Frank is your family too.

612
01:00:52,575 --> 01:00:54,575
But he's not here.

613
01:00:57,932 --> 01:01:00,333
And now, neither is our daughter.

614
01:01:04,559 --> 01:01:06,704
It's not your fault.

615
01:01:09,210 --> 01:01:12,548
It's not even Randall's
fault, not this time.

616
01:01:14,869 --> 01:01:16,369
It's my fault.

617
01:01:18,953 --> 01:01:20,386
(SIGHING)

618
01:01:20,429 --> 01:01:22,126
(SPEAKING GAELIC)

619
01:01:24,392 --> 01:01:27,572
I asked your forgiveness once.

620
01:01:28,486 --> 01:01:31,158
You said there's nothing to forgive.

621
01:01:32,925 --> 01:01:34,925
Truth is...

622
01:01:38,458 --> 01:01:40,868
I already forgave you,

623
01:01:42,529 --> 01:01:44,430
long before today.

624
01:01:45,588 --> 01:01:49,290
For this and anything
else you could ever do.

625
01:01:54,355 --> 01:01:56,856
There is something else.

626
01:02:01,798 --> 01:02:04,212
I slept with the king.

627
01:02:05,776 --> 01:02:07,556
To buy your freedom.

628
01:02:15,509 --> 01:02:17,813
You did it to save my life.

629
01:02:23,918 --> 01:02:27,189
Just like I gave myself
to Randall to save you.

630
01:02:42,437 --> 01:02:44,501
How can we ever be the same?

631
01:02:45,972 --> 01:02:47,790
No, we can't be.

632
01:02:50,876 --> 01:02:53,399
The weight of what has
happened here is...

633
01:02:54,816 --> 01:02:58,250
too much for any one
of us to bear alone.

634
01:03:05,260 --> 01:03:06,425
The only way we can live with it

635
01:03:06,461 --> 01:03:08,127
is to carry it...

636
01:03:10,965 --> 01:03:12,131
together.

637
01:03:14,402 --> 01:03:16,783
Are you sure you want to do that?

638
01:03:17,842 --> 01:03:19,517
We lost our child.

639
01:03:21,142 --> 01:03:25,411
But by the grace of God,
we may be given another.

640
01:03:29,920 --> 01:03:30,758
Then bring me home.

641
01:03:34,526 --> 01:03:35,691
To Scotland.

642
01:03:37,592 --> 01:03:38,757
Aye.

643
01:03:42,630 --> 01:03:43,229
Scotland.

644
01:03:44,499 --> 01:03:47,720
But there's something
I'd like to do first.

645
01:03:52,390 --> 01:03:55,400
<i>♪</i>

646
01:03:56,544 --> 01:03:58,544
St. Andrew.

647
01:04:12,894 --> 01:04:15,658
If we must bury you here in France,

648
01:04:17,498 --> 01:04:19,728
let's leave a bit of Scotland wi' ye.

649
01:04:20,658 --> 01:04:23,669
<i>♪</i>

